recordings.loc: Skidaway Island, Chatham County, GA USA
recordings.type: alarm call, call, mixture of threat and other calls at rookery
recordings.rmk:
Birds at a mixed rookery bordering a water feature. Individuals were jockeying for breeding space.  In addition to Great Egrets and Little Blue Herons the rookery had a few Green Herons and Tri-colored Herons as well. I was trying for a characteristic gargling sound of the Snowy on the nest.  

I applied a light high pass filter trying to rid the recording of an incessant industrial fan  - to little avail.

recordings.loc: Palo Alto, Santa Clara County, California
recordings.type: nesting birds in a rookery with large chicks, all manner of behavior: begging, s
recordings.file-name: XC215738-snowy egrets Palo Alto shoreline 12 May 2012 late morning.mp3
recordings.rmk:
The location of this Snowy Egret Rookery is near a freeway and a municipal airfield, in a park criss-crossed with bike lanes and pedestrian trails. I have edited out the loudest planes and other sound sources, but I have not compressed or otherwise filtered the sound. I would have marked it as C, except for the birds being so front and center in the recordings. No doubt the egrets are having to shout to be heard over the din on humanity at this busy site.

The rookery had at least thirty active nests; a few are occupied by Black-crowned Night Herons. It is spread over several trees of different species. Nest are about 5 to 7 meters off the ground. All conceivable nesting behaviors were occurring - begging by adults and juveniles, display, copulation, feeding, disciplining of juveniles, greeting returning mates, aggression toward other nesters, alarm calls regarding crows. The calls are continuous - very little air. 

It was a clear and warm May day by the south shore of San Francisco Bay, nearly no wind. This rookery has not been active since 2012 - California is experiencing a severe drought; salinity of the bay has risen because of lack of freshwater run-off. Snowies have successfully nested in some nearby locations since 2012, but in reduced numbers.

About 90 Snowy Egrets were feeding in relatively close quarters in shallow water in a rice field, many of which were chasing one another around while fighting for space.  All of the roaring calls and the little horn-like calls were from the snowies. Black-bellied Whistling Ducks sang for about 30 sec starting at 0:15 (esp at about 0:32 to 0:46).  A Great Egret called distantly at 1:05. There are no cuts within this recording.
